Understanding CLI(command line interface)

  1. What is a Command-Line Interface (CLI)?

Imagine talking to your computer by typing out commands instead of clicking on icons and menus like you do in a regular desktop environment. Thats what the CLI is a text-based way to interact with your computer.
Unlike the Graphical User Interface (GUI), where you use a mouse to navigate, the CLI requires you to type specific instructions to get things done.

  1. What is a Shell?

The shell is like your computers translator. When you type a command, the shell takes your input and tells the computer what to do. Think of it as the middleman between you and the computers operating system.
There are different types of shells, but one of the most common in Linux is called Bash (which stands for Bourne Again SHell). Bash makes it easier for you to interact with the system by providing helpful features like command history, scripting, and more.

  1. What is REPL (Read-Evaluate-Print Loop)? The shell operates in a cycle known as REPL, which stands for Read-Evaluate-Print Loop.
    Heres how it works:
  • Read: You type a command, and the shell reads it.
  • Evaluate: The shell interprets what youve typed and executes it.
  • Print: The shell shows you the result of the command.
  • Loop: This cycle repeats, meaning you can keep typing and running commands as long as you need.

The part of the operating system responsible for managing files and directories is called the file system. It organizes our data into files, which hold information, and directories (also called folders), which hold files or other directories. Shell expansion:

In both cases (cd ~ and cd $HOME), the shell performs an expansion before executing the command:

Tilde expansion cd ~: The shell expands the special character ~ to the path of the home directory. Variable expansion cd $HOME: The shell expands $HOME to the actual path stored in the environment variable.

Type the command whoami, then press the Enter key (Mac OS = Return) to send the command to the shell. The commands output is the ID of the current user, i.e., it shows us who the shell thinks we are:

At any moment, our current working directory is our current default directory, i.e., the directory that the computer assumes we want to run commands in unless we explicitly specify something else.

Directories in the Linux Root Filesystem in HCC

To view the directories and files present in the root directory (/) of the HCC system, we can use the ls command. The root directory is the top-level directory in the filesystem hierarchy.

You can list the contents of the root directory using the following command:

ls /
bin  boot  common  cvmfs  dev  etc  home  lib  lib64  lustre  media  mnt  opt  proc  rgi  root  run  sbin  scratch  srv  sys  tmp  usr  util  var  work
  1. /home

The /home directory is where user-specific files and directories are stored. Each user has a subdirectory within /home, such as /home/john for a user named John. This is where personal documents, configurations, and other data specific to the user are kept.

  1. /work

The /work directory is typically used for project-specific or work-related data. Its a custom directory that organizations or users create to store files related to specific tasks, projects, or ongoing work.

  1. /usr

The /usr directory is where user applications and utilities are stored. It includes subdirectories like /usr/bin for user executables and /usr/lib for libraries.

 which pwd
/usr/bin/pwd

What is an argument/flag/option ??

An argument is a value provided to a command to modify its behavior.

ls is the command used to list directory contents. -F is an argument (specifically, an option or flag) that tells ls to add a character to the end of each listed item, indicating its type (e.g., / for directories)

what if we run ls -F /data (with a leading slash) ??

ls -F /data # list contents of /data directory present in root
ls: cannot access '/data': No such file or directory

ls -F / # list contents of the root (/) directory with file type indicators
bin@  dev/  home/  lib32@ libx32@  mnt/ rocker_scripts/  sbin@  srv/  usr/   work/ boot/    environment@  init*  lib64@  lustre/  opt/ root/ scratch/ sys/  util/ common/  etc/   lib@   libexec/  media/ proc/  run/  singularity@  tmp/  var/

  • / (Slash):

    Indicates a Directory: When a name ends with a /, it means that the item is a directory (folder) where other files and directories are stored.

    Example: home/, usr/

  • @ (At Symbol):

    Indicates a Symbolic Link: A symbolic link (symlink) is like a shortcut or alias to another file or directory. The @ indicates that the item is a link pointing to another location.

    Example: bin@, lib64@

  • * (Asterisk):

    Indicates an Executable File: If a name ends with an *, it means that the file is executable, meaning it can be run as a program or script.

    Example: init*

We now know how to go down the directory tree: how do we go up? We could use an absolute path:but its almost always simpler to use cd .. to go up one level:

cd ..
pwd

.. is a special directory name meaning parent of the current directory. if we run pwd after running cd .., were back in /xx/xxx/filesystem/Users/nelle/

Kindly note: xxx represents the absolute path to the location of the nelle directory. This path may differ for each user because the home directory varies from one user to another.

Considering that all the users are currently in the directory nelle we will further explore the file hierarchy

The special directory .. doesnt usually show up when we run ls. If we want to display it, we can give ls the -a flag:

ls -F -a
./                  creatures/          notes.txt
../                 data/               pizza.cfg
.bash_profile       molecules/          solar.pdf
Desktop/            north-pacific-gyre/ writing/

-a stands for show all; it forces ls to show us file and directory names that begin with ., such as .. (which, if were in xx/Users/nelle, refers to the /Users directory). As you can see, it also displays another special directory thats just called ., which means the current working directory. It may seem redundant to have a name for it, but well see some uses for it soon.

Finally, we also see a file called .bash_profile. This file usually contains settings to customize the shell (terminal).

lets explore the permission string

  • d or -: Indicates file type (d for directory, - for regular file).
  • rwxr-xr-x: Represents permissions for the owner, group, and others.
  • Categories of Users

    • Owner (User): The first three characters.

    • Group: The next three characters.

    • Others: The last three characters.

    • r (read): View file contents or list directory.

    • w (write): Modify file or directory contents.

    • x (execute): Run the file or access the directory.

Module 3 : Creating & Delete Things

We now know how to explore files and directories, but how do we create them in the first place? Lets go back to Nelles home directory, cd ~/filesystem/Users/nelle, and use ls -F to see what it contains:

cd ~/filesystem/Users/nelle
ls -F
creatures/  molecules/           pizza.cfg
data/       north-pacific-gyre/  solar.pdf
Desktop/    notes.txt            writing/

Lets create a new directory called thesis using the command mkdir thesis (which has no output):

mkdir thesis

mkdir means make directory. Since thesis is a relative path (i.e., doesnt have a leading slash), the new directory is created in the current working directory, lets verify it

ls -F
Desktop/  creatures/  data/  molecules/  north-pacific-gyre/ 
notes.txt  pizza.cfg  solar.pdf  thesis/  writing/

However, theres nothing in it yet:

ls -F thesis

One of the simplest ways to create an empty file is via the touch command. Change the working directory to thesis using cd, then touch an empty file called draft.txt:

cd thesis
touch draft.txt # create an empty file

If we check the directory contents now,

ls -F .  # or ls -F
draft.txt

Lets remove the text file using rm, the command used to remove files and directories . We will use -i flag to for removal confirmation.

rm -i draft.txt
rm: remove regular empty file 'draft.txt'? y

To proceed with the deletion, you should type y (for yes) and press Enter.

lets confirm the deletion of the file using ls

ls

Now lets run a text editor called Nano to create a file called draft.txt( this is an another way to create a bew file)

nano draft.txt

Lets type in a few lines of text, then use Control-O to write our data to disk (press enter):

Nano in action

Once our file is saved, we can use Control-X to quit the editor and return to the shell. (Unix documentation often uses the shorthand ^A to mean control-A.).

Press Control-O (^O) to save your file.
Press Control-X (^X) to exit the editor.

nano doesnt leave any output on the screen after it exits, but ls now shows that we have created a file called draft.txt:

ls
draft.txt

Lets tidy up by running rm draft.txt:

rm draft.txt

Important: Deleting is forever

The Unix shell doesnt have a trash bin that we can recover deleted files from . Instead, when we delete files, they are unhooked from the file system so that their storage space on disk can be recycled.

Lets re-create that file using nano and then move up one directory to ~/filesystem/Users/nelle using cd ..:

pwd

you will get the absolute path like this

/home/t32decode/<your-username>/filesystem/Users/nelle/thesis

lets create the file

touch draft.txt
ls
draft.txt

move 1 dir up

 cd ..
 ls
Desktop  creatures  data  molecules  north-pacific-gyre  
notes.txt  pizza.cfg  solar.pdf  thesis  writing

if we try to remove the entire thesis directory using rm thesis, we get an error message:

rm thesis
rm: cannot remove 'thesis/': Is a directory

This happens because rm only works on files, not directories. The right command is rmdir, which is short for remove directory. It doesnt work yet either, though, because the directory were trying to remove isnt empty:

rmdir thesis
rmdir: failed to remove 'thesis/': Directory not empty

This little safety feature can save you a lot of grief, particularly if you are a bad typist. To really get rid of thesis we must first delete the file draft.txt:

rm thesis/draft.txt  # use tab for autocompletion

The directory is now empty, so rmdir can delete it:

rmdir thesis
With Great Power Comes Great Responsibility

Removing the files in a directory just so that we can remove the directory quickly becomes tedious. Instead, we can use rm with the -r flag (which stands for recursive): 

$ rm -r thesis

This removes everything in the directory, then the directory itself. If the directory contains sub-directories, rm -r does the same thing to them, and so on. Its very handy, but can do a lot of damage if used without care. 

mkdir thesis           # create directory named thesis
touch thesis/draft.txt # create empty file named draft.txt inside thesis directory
ls thesis              # list contents of thesis directory to verify draft.txt exists
rm -ri thesis          # remove thesis directory and its contents interactively, 
                       # prompting for confirmation before each file/directory deletion
rm: descend into directory 'thesis'? y
rm: remove regular empty file 'thesis/draft.txt'? y
rm: remove directory 'thesis'? y

Lets create that directory and file one more time.

mkdir thesis           
touch thesis/draft.txt 
ls thesis
draft.txt

draft.txt isnt a particularly informative name, so lets change the files name using mv, which is short for move:

mv thesis/draft.txt thesis/quotes.txt  # Rename file "draft.txt" to "quotes.txt" within "thesis" dir

The first parameter tells mv what were moving, while the second is where its to go. In this case, were moving thesis/draft.txt to thesis/quotes.txt, which has the same effect as renaming the file.

ls thesis
quotes.txt

Lets move quotes.txt into the current working directory( can be specified using .). We use mv , but this time well just use name of a directory as the second parameter to tell mv that we want to keep the filename, but put the file somewhere new. (This is why the command is called move.)

pwd
mv thesis/quotes.txt .  # . means current directory
ls
Desktop  creatures  data  molecules  north-pacific-gyre  
notes.txt  pizza.cfg  quotes.txt  solar.pdf  thesis  writing

The effect is to move the file from the directory it was in to the current working directory.

Remember:

  1. Renaming Files or Directories: Use mv old_name new_name to rename a file or directory.
  2. Moving Files or Directories: Use mv file_name target_directory/ to move a file or directory to a new location. If you want to move it to the current directory, use . as the target

The cp command works very much like mv, except it copies a file instead of moving it. We can check that it did the right thing using ls with two paths as parameters like most Unix commands, ls can be given thousands of paths at once:

cp quotes.txt thesis/quotations.txt # Copy file "quotes.txt" to "thesis" directory with new name "quotations.txt"
ls quotes.txt thesis/quotations.txt # List both "quotes.txt" and "thesis/quotations.txt" to verify

quotes.txt  thesis/quotations.txt

To prove that we made a copy, lets delete the quotes.txt file in the current directory and then run that same ls again.

rm quotes.txt
ls quotes.txt thesis/quotations.txt
ls: cannot access 'quotes.txt': No such file or directory
thesis/quotations.txt

This time it tells us that it cant find quotes.txt in the current directory, but it does find the copy in thesis that we didnt delete.

Quizz time

Suppose that you created a .txt file in your current directory to contain a list of the statistical tests you will need to do to analyze your data, and named it: statstics.txt

After creating and saving this file you realize you misspelled the filename! You want to correct the mistake, which of the following commands could you use to do so?

1. cp statstics.txt statistics.txt
2. mv statstics.txt statistics.txt
3. mv statstics.txt .
4. cp statstics.txt .

Hint: Consider whether you want to keep the original file and create a new one with the correct name, or if you simply want to change the existing files name. One of these commands directly renames the file, which is the quickest way to fix the typo without leaving a duplicate.

Module 4 : Pipes and Filters

Now that we know a few basic commands, we can finally look at the shells most powerful feature: the ease with which it lets us combine existing programs in new ways. Well start with a directory called molecules that contains six .pdf files.

ls 
pwd
/home/t32decode/sujith/filesystem/Users/nelle

ls molecules
cubane.pdb    ethane.pdb    methane.pdb
octane.pdb    pentane.pdb   propane.pdb

Lets go into that directory with cd and run the command wc *.pdb. wc is the word count command: it counts the number of lines, words, and characters in files. The * in *.pdb matches zero or more characters, so the shell turns *.pdb into a complete list of .pdb files:

cd molecules
ls
wc *.pdb
cubane.pdb  ethane.pdb  methane.pdb  octane.pdb  pentane.pdb  propane.pdb

20  156 1158 cubane.pdb
  12   84  622 ethane.pdb
   9   57  422 methane.pdb
  30  246 1828 octane.pdb
  21  165 1226 pentane.pdb
  15  111  825 propane.pdb
 107  819 6081 total
  • First column (lines): The number of lines in the file.
  • Second column (words): The number of words in the file.
  • Third column (bytes/character): The total number of bytes in the file (which also represents the file size in bytes).

wildcard:

* is a wildcard. It matches zero or more characters, so *.pdb matches ethane.pdb, propane.pdb, and so on. On the other hand, p*.pdb only matches pentane.pdb and propane.pdb, because the p at the front only matches itself.

Lets view one of the file, we can use head to view the file

head -n 5 cubane.pdb # the n flag is used to specify number of lines displayed
COMPND      CUBANE
AUTHOR      DAVE WOODCOCK  95 12 06
ATOM      1  C           1       0.789  -0.852   0.504  1.00  0.00
ATOM      2  C           1      -0.161  -1.104  -0.624  1.00  0.00
ATOM      3  C           1      -1.262  -0.440   0.160  1.00  0.00

If we run wc -l instead of just wc, the output shows only the number of lines per file:

wc -l *.pdb
20  cubane.pdb
  12  ethane.pdb
   9  methane.pdb
  30  octane.pdb
  21  pentane.pdb
  15  propane.pdb
 107  total

We can also use -w to get only the number of words, or -c to get only the number of characters/bytes.

Which of these files is shortest?

cat methane.pdb
COMPND      METHANE
AUTHOR      DAVE WOODCOCK  95 12 18
ATOM      1  C           1       0.257  -0.363   0.000  1.00  0.00
ATOM      2  H           1       0.257   0.727   0.000  1.00  0.00
ATOM      3  H           1       0.771  -0.727   0.890  1.00  0.00
ATOM      4  H           1       0.771  -0.727  -0.890  1.00  0.00
ATOM      5  H           1      -0.771  -0.727   0.000  1.00  0.00
TER       6              1
END

Its an easy question to answer when there are only six files, but what if there were 6000? Our first step toward a solution is to run the command:

wc -l *.pdb > lengths.txt

The greater than symbol, >, tells the shell to redirect the commands output to a file instead of printing it to the screen. The shell will create the file if it doesnt exist, or overwrite the contents of that file if it does. (This is why there is no screen output: everything that wc would have printed has gone into the file lengths.txt instead.) ls confirms that the file exists:

ls
cubane.pdb  ethane.pdb  lengths.txt  methane.pdb  
octane.pdb  pentane.pdb  propane.pdb

We can now send the content of lengths.txt to the screen using cat lengths.txt. cat stands for concatenate: it prints the contents of files one after another. Theres only one file in this case, so cat just shows us what it contains:

cat lengths.txt
20 cubane.pdb
  12 ethane.pdb
   9 methane.pdb
  30 octane.pdb
  21 pentane.pdb
  15 propane.pdb
 107 total

Now lets use the sort command to sort its contents. We will also use the -n flag to specify that the sort is numerical instead of alphabetical. This does not change the file; instead, it sends the sorted result to the screen:

sort -n lengths.txt
9 methane.pdb
  12 ethane.pdb
  15 propane.pdb
  20 cubane.pdb
  21 pentane.pdb
  30 octane.pdb
 107 total

We can put the sorted list of lines in another temporary file called sorted-lengths.txt by putting > sorted-lengths.txt after the command, just as we used > lengths.txt to put the output of wc into lengths.txt.

Once weve done that, we can run another command called head to get the first few lines in sorted-lengths.txt:

sort -n lengths.txt > sorted-lengths.txt
ls 
cubane.pdb  ethane.pdb  lengths.txt  
methane.pdb  octane.pdb  pentane.pdb  
propane.pdb  sorted-lengths.txt

lets run the head command now

head -1 sorted-lengths.txt
9 methane.pdb

Using the parameter -1 with head tells it that we only want the first line of the file; -20 would get the first 20, and so on. Since sorted-lengths.txt contains the lengths of our files ordered from least to greatest, the output of head must be the file with the fewest lines.

lets make the process easier by running sort and head together, instead of creating an intermediate file.

sort -n lengths.txt | head -1
9 methane.pdb

what happend here ????

The vertical bar(|) between the two commands is called a pipe. It tells the shell that we want to use the output of the command on the left as the input to the command on the right.

We can use another pipe to send the output of wc directly to sort, which then sends its output to head, without creating any intermediate file.

wc -l *.pdb | sort -n | head -1
9 methane.pdb

This is exactly like a mathematician nesting functions like log(3x) and saying the log of three times x. In our case, the calculation is head of sort of line count of *.pdb.

Lets find the file with the most lines.

wc -l *.pdb | sort -nr | head -1
107 total

The issue is wc -l command includes a summary line with the total number of lines across all files. You can use grep to filter out line containing total before passing the output to sort:

grep is a command used to search for specific patterns in the input text. In this case, it searches for the word total. The -v option inverts the search, meaning it excludes any lines that match the pattern total.

wc -l *.pdb | grep -v 'total'| sort -nr | head -1
30 octane.pdb

Module 5 : Short intro to loops

Wildcards and tab completion are two ways to reduce typing (and typing mistakes). Another way is to tell the shell to do something over and over again. Suppose we have several hundred genome data files named basilisk.dat, unicorn.dat, and so on. In this example, well use the creatures directory which only has two example files, but the principles can be applied to many many more files at once. We would like to copy these files and rename as copy-basilisk.dat and copy-unicorn.dat, but also save a version of original files.

# use the absolute path to get back to nelle directory 
cd /home/t32decode/<your-username>/filesystem/Users/nelle/
# or use
cd .. # go 1 level up in directory tree

# the change to creatures dir using 
cd creatures
ls
basilisk.dat  unicorn.dat

Before starting with the loop, we need to know what a variable is using the echo command. Below is an example for demonstration

filename="basilisk.dat"
echo $filename

filename=basilisk.dat:

Here, youre assigning the string basilisk.dat to the variable filename. A variable is a placeholder for storing information that can be reused.

The echo command outputs the value of the variable to the terminal. The $ before filename is used to retrieve the value stored in the variable.

lets understand what is happening inside the for loop using echo command

for filename in *.dat
do
    echo "Copying $filename to copy-$filename"
done
Copying basilisk.dat to copy-basilisk.dat
Copying unicorn.dat to copy-unicorn.dat

The loop iterates over each .dat file in the current directory. On each iteration, the filename variable is assigned the name of one file.

echo "Copying $filename to copy-$filename": This line will print a message to the terminal, showing exactly what the loop is doing at each step.

for filename in *.dat
do
    cp $filename copy-$filename
done

lets confirm the copyinng

ls
basilisk.dat  copy-basilisk.dat  copy-unicorn.dat  unicorn.dat

You can also use single line for loop (using semi-colons to separate the pieces)as given below

for filename in *.dat; do echo "$filename copy-$filename"; done
